g.text: EMILY M. ENG / THE SEATTLE TIMES
EMILY M. ENG / THE SEATTLE TIMES
Source: Marla Holt, National Atmospheric and Oceanic Administration, Northwest Fisheries Science Center

text.tspan: Southern resident killer whales specialize in hunting salmon, and use a range of clicks and buzzes to target, pursue
and capture their prey. They also make pulsed calls to communicate with each other. Here is a re-creation with
sound of an actual dive by southern resident orca K35, made from a recording in 2014 on a temporary acoustic tag
on the whale. K35 was born in 2002 and made this dive between Hein and Salmon Bank off San Juan Island.
